00:01:57.909 --> 00:02:00.550
&gt;&gt;JP:
[Indian accent]

00:02:00.550 --> 00:02:08.750
Friends, I'm delighted to be here with you.
Oftentimes, when somebody is very tall, there's

00:02:08.750 --> 00:02:16.110
a natural advantage in life. For once, I found
that [presenter] being very tall was a disadvantage.

00:02:16.110 --> 00:02:23.170
The microphone was a little, at a lower level
and I was amused by this idea that what appears

00:02:23.170 --> 00:02:27.050
to be of great advantage sometimes could actually
be a problem on occasion.

00:02:27.050 --> 00:02:32.230
I think that's important when we discover
things about a society, about a nation, about

00:02:32.230 --> 00:02:44.610
an economy, and in many ways about many organizations.
I was asked to make a few points about Indian

00:02:44.610 --> 00:02:54.060
economy and politics and I've chosen the theme:
19th-century Politics and 21st-century Economy.

00:02:54.060 --> 00:03:00.960
Can they coexist and if there are some serious
issues here, what can we do to make things

00:03:00.960 --> 00:03:02.930
better?

00:03:02.930 --> 00:03:10.370
If the 20th century offered us any lessons,
it is that you cannot delink economics from

00:03:10.370 --> 00:03:17.901
politics. The biggest question decided by
the 20th century will allow us whether or

00:03:17.901 --> 00:03:23.790
not the socialist economy was right or the
market economy was right. It's a central political

00:03:23.790 --> 00:03:24.790
question.

00:03:24.790 --> 00:03:32.770
Ultimately, we recognize that the economic
growth of a country is not neutral to the

00:03:32.770 --> 00:03:40.480
political trajectory of that nation. And in
1991, when the Berlin Wall collapsed, in '89

00:03:40.480 --> 00:03:46.040
when the Berlin Wall collapsed, in '91 when
The Soviet Union collapsed and much of the

00:03:46.040 --> 00:03:53.900
world embraced market economy, but with certain
changes; certain significant changes. Then,

00:03:53.900 --> 00:04:01.120
the assumption of the world is that humankind
has discovered what works best in terms of

00:04:01.120 --> 00:04:05.910
economic growth and political organization.

00:04:05.910 --> 00:04:14.010
But, I think we all should recognize that's
not an unadulterated victory of market economy.

00:04:14.010 --> 00:04:19.799
The market economy won because they have actually
absorbed some of the socialist principles.

00:04:19.799 --> 00:04:24.470
In the first half of the 20th century, education
and healthcare were not regarded as government's

00:04:24.470 --> 00:04:29.430
business. But, in the second half of the 20th
century, most every major country in the world

00:04:29.430 --> 00:04:36.020
of any consequence embraced both education
and healthcare as part of governments business.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:40.240
The services may be provided by the private
sector, but it must be driven by the public

00:04:40.240 --> 00:04:44.680
sector; just a broader understanding. In a
many-, very fundamental sense, it is this

00:04:44.680 --> 00:04:50.160
synthesis of some of the socialist principles
with a market economy that made a success

00:04:50.160 --> 00:04:51.680
of market economy possible.

00:04:51.680 --> 00:05:03.010
Therefore, I would like to start off my presentation
with a brief discussion of the role of state.

00:05:03.010 --> 00:05:06.590
What is it that the modern state should be
doing? It should be debating whether it should

00:05:06.590 --> 00:05:12.010
be socialist or market based. What is the
role of the state? In India, this question

00:05:12.010 --> 00:05:18.310
has never been adequately addressed. I would
like to argue that the state is primarily

00:05:18.310 --> 00:05:23.380
meant for public order, justice, and rule
of law; apart from the difference of the [inaudible

00:05:23.380 --> 00:05:29.220
 ] so on and so forth. And then it must be
essentially to enhance the capabilities of

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:30.420
the citizens of the societies--

00:05:30.420 --> 00:05:31.420
[phone rings]

00:05:31.420 --> 00:05:35.930
of the society, so that the accident of birth,
"accident of the womb", as Warren Buffet called

00:05:35.930 --> 00:05:42.930
it, does not determine the fate of the child.
And that is education and healthcare. And

00:05:42.930 --> 00:05:48.350
then, of course, infrastructure required for
a modern economy, in particular, transport

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:52.240
and powers technical, communications, thanks
to all of you guys; the government's role

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:58.710
is now very marginal except minimal regulation,
really. And the natural resources development

00:05:58.710 --> 00:06:03.400
there's no way anybody but a straight actor
is going to do something like Tennessee Valley

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:09.330
Authority, or the Hoover Dam. It has to be
a governments business. And finally, social

00:06:09.330 --> 00:06:12.950
security, a measure of social security so
that those who fall into the cracks, their

00:06:12.950 --> 00:06:19.590
concerns can be addressed in a humane modern
society. Once we look at state and its role

00:06:19.590 --> 00:06:24.850
with greater clarity in this manner, I think
a lot of questions can be addressed much better.

00:06:24.850 --> 00:06:32.630
The economic story of India, in the past 10,
15, 20 years, is by now reasonably well understood

00:06:32.630 --> 00:06:41.290
across the world. In 1947, we start with 2%
to the global GDP. There is something called

00:06:41.290 --> 00:06:49.169
global GDP. But, not too long ago in human
history terms, about three centuries, four

00:06:49.169 --> 00:06:57.440
centuries before that, India shape of economic,
the world economy was something like 25%.

00:06:57.440 --> 00:07:02.990
But all until 150 to 200 years because we
did not even take advantage of the Industrial

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:09.540
Revolution. India fell to 2% of the global
GDP. By 1991, this fell down to 1% of the

00:07:09.540 --> 00:07:17.330
GDP. The economy in India grew at a snail's
pace, but in terms of the global economy,

00:07:17.330 --> 00:07:24.139
our share came down to 1%. In 1991, as we
all know now, the current Prime Minister as

00:07:24.139 --> 00:07:29.390
Finance Minister of India, in the wake of
an enormous crisis, out of compulsion, not

00:07:29.390 --> 00:07:35.370
conviction, engineered and made a U-turn in
our economic policies.

00:07:35.370 --> 00:07:42.470
Today, we are back at 2% of the global GDP.
In other words, we ran very hard for 63 years

00:07:42.470 --> 00:07:46.730
to remain where we were. In related terms,
not that India hasn't progressed at all, but

00:07:46.730 --> 00:07:55.020
we're still the way we were in 1947. But,
the general perception is with a reasonably

00:07:55.020 --> 00:08:03.000
good growth rates, those cannot matching China's,
and with some everyday stuff, sustaining those

00:08:03.000 --> 00:08:09.389
growth rates, India could well be one of the
major economies of the world in the next few

00:08:09.389 --> 00:08:10.389
decades.

00:08:10.389 --> 00:08:16.371
The emerging markets forum say it's by 2039.
If India does a few things right, we could

00:08:16.371 --> 00:08:21.330
well be the second largest economy in the
world. That China will be the largest is more

00:08:21.330 --> 00:08:25.770
or less accepted now, I think. There are a
very few people in the world who say that

00:08:25.770 --> 00:08:31.520
anything else is possible now. But the future,
of course, may tell us a different story.

00:08:31.520 --> 00:08:37.800
Whether India will actually fulfill our potential
is a great challenge. My argument is India

00:08:37.800 --> 00:08:44.730
has the potential to achieve this miracle,
but we are to make this miracle happen. Our

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:49.449
politics has become now a great impediment
to economic growth and to fulfilling India's

00:08:49.449 --> 00:08:50.449
potential.

00:08:50.449 --> 00:08:55.519
[pause]

00:08:55.519 --> 00:09:00.689
If you look at politics of India in the past
60 years, there's a huge success story. At

00:09:00.689 --> 00:09:07.399
one level, India is the first country in the
world to embrace universal adult franchise

00:09:07.399 --> 00:09:14.110
on the first day that the Constitution was
written. For largely illiterate and extremely

00:09:14.110 --> 00:09:22.300
poor country, to embrace adult franchise on
a universal basis from day one was actually

00:09:22.300 --> 00:09:30.709
a great adventure. It was an enormous expression
of faith in the wisdom of the bulk of the

00:09:30.709 --> 00:09:33.269
people of the country.

00:09:33.269 --> 00:09:40.149
This very great country in which we are right
now: the first republic in the modern world,

00:09:40.149 --> 00:09:45.569
the first democracy in the modern world, the
first country to practice abolition of powers,

00:09:45.569 --> 00:09:50.889
the first country with a written constitution,
despite recognition that all human beings

00:09:50.889 --> 00:09:58.529
are equal, it took them something like, 144
years after those immortal words written in

00:09:58.529 --> 00:10:01.959
The Declaration of Independence to recognize
that women are equal to men.

00:10:01.959 --> 00:10:09.290
It took a civil war and the sacrifice and
the blood and gore of more than ten thousand

00:10:09.290 --> 00:10:15.249
able-bodied youth of this country to recognize
that people of another skin color are the

00:10:15.249 --> 00:10:21.009
same as any other skin color. Even in that
context, and given the fact that Britain took

00:10:21.009 --> 00:10:26.769
centuries before women got the right to vote
in 1928, it was actually remarkable expression

00:10:26.769 --> 00:10:32.060
of faith and the part of Indian Constitution
make us to recognize that all Indians, irrespective

00:10:32.060 --> 00:10:36.899
of caste, religion, language, and we have
many, many, many languages even here. I'm

00:10:36.899 --> 00:10:42.279
sure many people do not realize how many languages
there are in India, serious languages for

00:10:42.279 --> 00:10:48.689
thousands of years history, hundreds of years
history, their own literature, their own script,

00:10:48.689 --> 00:10:49.689
and their own unique culture.

00:10:49.689 --> 00:10:51.730
[pause]

00:10:51.730 --> 00:10:57.970
Despite all this, and despite the fact that
India was actually partitioned on the basis

00:10:57.970 --> 00:11:05.089
of religion, the Indian Constitution make
us put enormous faith in the people of the

00:11:05.089 --> 00:11:10.709
country. And in some respects, I think that
faith is fully vindicated.

00:11:10.709 --> 00:11:16.041
If you take India's political evolution, it's
a remarkable success story in the sense that:

00:11:16.041 --> 00:11:23.290
A. We retained our political freedoms. B.
There is intense electoral competition. Elections

00:11:23.290 --> 00:11:29.629
in India are not make-believe elections. C.
The winners do not punish the losers. There

00:11:29.629 --> 00:11:33.140
are many countries in the world where the
loser is punished merely because he lost the

00:11:33.140 --> 00:11:38.399
election. He may lose his head or liberty
or many things. In India that never happen,

00:11:38.399 --> 00:11:44.440
mercifully. And finally, the elected government
is truly an authority. It's not some [inaudible]

00:11:44.440 --> 00:11:45.440
agenda.

00:11:45.440 --> 00:11:53.889
Going by these four postulates, India is a
truly vibrant, functioning democracy. And

00:11:53.889 --> 00:11:58.509
that we could actually maintain a moderate
rate of growth t-, in the economy and now

00:11:58.509 --> 00:12:05.209
emerges a reasonably influential country in
terms of the future economy the globe.

00:12:05.209 --> 00:12:10.459
It's a source of some satisfaction. But the
fact is there are also many dark corners of

00:12:10.459 --> 00:12:16.300
Indian politics and unless they are set right,
unless we throw light on them, unless we change

00:12:16.300 --> 00:12:19.139
that, we may not fulfill our true economic
potential.

00:12:19.139 --> 00:12:23.860
[pause]

00:12:23.860 --> 00:12:31.920
Particularly, because India is largely poor
and because most people are still illiterate,

00:12:31.920 --> 00:12:38.120
because politics is in the power struggle
without any reference to ideologies or any

00:12:38.120 --> 00:12:43.800
outcomes, because there's increasing contention
in politics, but there's only a change of

00:12:43.800 --> 00:12:49.529
players and there's no change in the outcomes,
there's no change in the rules of the game;

00:12:49.529 --> 00:12:53.319
money has become the currency of politics.

00:12:53.319 --> 00:12:56.450
For those of you from the United States, it
might appear that's very normal thing in politics,

00:12:56.450 --> 00:13:00.600
after all the US has spent a lot of money
in politics. But those are two different worlds,

00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:06.649
altogether. The money spent here is entirely
for legitimate campaigning purposes; most

00:13:06.649 --> 00:13:16.449
of it for television advertising. It's fully
accounted. And it's transparent. Sadly, much

00:13:16.449 --> 00:13:21.629
of the money is spent in elections in India
is unaccounted and for illegitimate purposes,

00:13:21.629 --> 00:13:24.329
mostly for work buying with money and liquor.

00:13:24.329 --> 00:13:28.429
So the market economy actually works in the
politics of India. And that's what ought to

00:13:28.429 --> 00:13:35.500
be changed. The second perversion of Indian
politics is in a country of abject poverty,

00:13:35.500 --> 00:13:41.239
it's very easy for the governments to seduce
the workers, offering them all kinds of freebies;

00:13:41.239 --> 00:13:47.339
unsustainable in the long term, very detrimental
to public good, but in the short term there's

00:13:47.339 --> 00:13:52.809
always a way of persuading the worker that
they're free power, free color television,

00:13:52.809 --> 00:13:58.920
free rice, and every month some amount of
money, irrespective of everything else that

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:01.379
that will be given once the government resumes
office.

00:14:01.379 --> 00:14:06.790
I'm not mention this things as casual. These
are all a real sore spot in India by political

00:14:06.790 --> 00:14:11.160
parties; some of them actually were delivered.
There is state of time in order where every

00:14:11.160 --> 00:14:15.160
family was offered a color television. And
they were actually delivered in significant

00:14:15.160 --> 00:14:18.689
measure. I don't know how many were delivered
finally, but millions of color televisions

00:14:18.689 --> 00:14:21.459
were delivered by the elected government as
part of the promise that they made to the

00:14:21.459 --> 00:14:26.799
electorate befor election. So increasingly,
parties resort to this kind of thing; taking

00:14:26.799 --> 00:14:32.790
advantage of the poverty. The third is, of
course, in a very diverse country with many

00:14:32.790 --> 00:14:36.649
primordial loyalties, it's very easy to divide
the people in caste, region, religion, and

00:14:36.649 --> 00:14:42.779
language. And mobilize them as working blocks,
with orders and stuff, "What's in it for me

00:14:42.779 --> 00:14:48.290
if I work for this party or that party?" Because
there's no, there's no sense that any party

00:14:48.290 --> 00:14:53.410
would make any difference, therefore, there's
only emotional purchase available.

00:14:53.410 --> 00:14:58.889
Once we have these three attitudes in politics,
which are increasingly dominant in the mainstream

00:14:58.889 --> 00:15:04.809
political parties, we have seen this crisis.
We have elections, we help peaceful transfer

00:15:04.809 --> 00:15:08.910
of power, we have fierce contention, we have
liberty, but political outcomes are simply

00:15:08.910 --> 00:15:14.749
not what India needs and that's what ought
to be changed.

00:15:14.749 --> 00:15:19.610
And therefore, my argument is that this kind
of a 19th-century political mode, a medieval

00:15:19.610 --> 00:15:24.029
political mode where politics is all about
power struggle, when we master the art of

00:15:24.029 --> 00:15:31.089
getting into power without bothering about
the outcomes, that cannot be coexist in the

00:15:31.089 --> 00:15:34.559
21st-century economy. One of them has to give
in. Either the politics must change, or the

00:15:34.559 --> 00:15:38.389
economy will eventually decline and collapse.

00:15:38.389 --> 00:15:41.590
What will happen depends on what we do in
the next ten years or so in India.

00:15:41.590 --> 00:15:49.449
A comparison with China would be very apt
because many people, obviously, are interested

00:15:49.449 --> 00:15:54.089
in the two Asian giants in terms of population
we're now more number two, respectively. In

00:15:54.089 --> 00:15:58.079
terms of growth based upon large economies,
now China is number one and India is pretty

00:15:58.079 --> 00:16:03.129
close to being number two. And in terms of
potential, India could well emerge as one

00:16:03.129 --> 00:16:07.249
of the economic giants of the world in the
next 30 years if we do well.

00:16:07.249 --> 00:16:12.679
So obviously, comparisons are inevitable.
But I think one, one has to understand things

00:16:12.679 --> 00:16:18.420
in perspective. One argument often advanced
is that China is not a democracy; therefore,

00:16:18.420 --> 00:16:20.569
they can do pretty much what they want.

00:16:20.569 --> 00:16:26.249
And therefore, they can actually focus on
excellence in economic growth even at the

00:16:26.249 --> 00:16:30.299
cost of short term political price. Because
after all, one of the great challenges of

00:16:30.299 --> 00:16:35.649
democratic politics anywhere in the world
is the conflict between the short term political

00:16:35.649 --> 00:16:43.069
price you have to pay for pursuing right policies,
and the long term, slow rate of social payoff

00:16:43.069 --> 00:16:45.339
is one of the most difficult things anywhere
in the world.

00:16:45.339 --> 00:16:48.899
That's why we all love to hate politicians,
because politicians are present with this

00:16:48.899 --> 00:16:53.691
all the time. They have to reconcile confronting
interests and satisfy all groups, and they

00:16:53.691 --> 00:16:58.149
have to be mindful of the short term political
price and yet focus on the long term public

00:16:58.149 --> 00:17:04.470
good. These are awesome challenges. Obviously,
in a dictatorship you don't have this problems;

00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:06.860
it's easier.

00:17:06.860 --> 00:17:13.920
Nevertheless, I think we're always taken the
case when we try and say that democracy is

00:17:13.920 --> 00:17:18.610
detrimental to economic growth. I would like
to argue that almost everything good that

00:17:18.610 --> 00:17:24.620
happen in China is actually because of the
democratization of society. And almost everything

00:17:24.620 --> 00:17:32.810
bad that happen in China after the October
rev-, 1948 revolution was because Chinese

00:17:32.810 --> 00:17:37.400
leadership on occasion acted autocratically
in an arbitrary manner.

00:17:37.400 --> 00:17:44.400
Take the later case, The Great Leap Forward,
between 1959 and '62, because of Mao Zedong's

00:17:44.400 --> 00:17:52.539
actually irrational policies, arbitrary policies,
20 million Chinese starved to death. 1959

00:17:52.539 --> 00:17:53.840
to '62 was not because of

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:58.190
[pause]

00:17:58.190 --> 00:18:03.990
any sensible policies. The autocracy of China
actually caused perhaps the greatest man-made

00:18:03.990 --> 00:18:11.440
misery in the 20th century. Similarly, the
Cultural Revolution of the 1960s, it was again

00:18:11.440 --> 00:18:15.809
another initial blunder. But the good things
that happened in China are because they tried

00:18:15.809 --> 00:18:22.389
to democratize: education, healthcare access,
decentralization of power, technology to villages,

00:18:22.389 --> 00:18:27.790
enhancing productivity; these are all clues
of democratization. An authoritarian leadership

00:18:27.790 --> 00:18:34.380
actually enhanced the contingent democracy.
We always think in terms of democracy as merely

00:18:34.380 --> 00:18:41.080
working. Democracy is more than that. We have
in India great liberty, but are we a democratic

00:18:41.080 --> 00:18:46.909
society fully in some respects? I suspect
not. In some respects, I dare to argue that

00:18:46.909 --> 00:18:52.169
China is perhaps more democratic than India.
You take the local governments in China. They

00:18:52.169 --> 00:18:54.679
are far more influential.

00:18:54.679 --> 00:18:59.240
There's far greater decentralization of power.
There is greater citizen empowerment at the

00:18:59.240 --> 00:19:03.690
local level then in India today. Everything
in India revolves on the Prime Minister, the

00:19:03.690 --> 00:19:09.639
Chief Minister at the provincial level and
the District Magistrate at the district level.

00:19:09.639 --> 00:19:15.470
The citizens and the communities and the local
governments have hardly any role at all. Similarly,

00:19:15.470 --> 00:19:19.740
education, healthcare, there's sense of a
modern democracy, have not been given the

00:19:19.740 --> 00:19:23.690
kind of importance that they deserved in India.

00:19:23.690 --> 00:19:28.340
What I'm arguing is the normative democracy
in terms of constitution and elections are

00:19:28.340 --> 00:19:32.980
necessary, but not sufficient. We have to
actually have a functioning democracy in terms

00:19:32.980 --> 00:19:38.171
of society being democratized. In terms of
fu-, people's future being decided not by

00:19:38.171 --> 00:19:43.149
the accident of birth, accident of the womb,
but by their hard work.

00:19:43.149 --> 00:19:47.730
And the society must give an opportunity to
fulfill her true potential. In that sense,

00:19:47.730 --> 00:19:53.149
we have a lot to learn from China. This categorization,
crude categorization of something is a democracy,

00:19:53.149 --> 00:19:58.360
something is not, bears immediate uncertain
indicators is not sufficient. And India must

00:19:58.360 --> 00:20:06.700
learn with humility the art of democratization
for a society. If that is the case, what are

00:20:06.700 --> 00:20:10.740
the things India should do? I'll come to the
concluding part of my presentation so we can

00:20:10.740 --> 00:20:15.759
have some time for meaningful interaction.
Well, I'm making a controversial point. I'm

00:20:15.759 --> 00:20:20.809
well aware of that and I think it requires
some serious examination.

00:20:20.809 --> 00:20:25.480
First is local governments. One great thing
that happened in India is a maturation of

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:33.330
federalization. India is a multi-lingual country.
In a northern neighborhood in Canada, I've

00:20:33.330 --> 00:20:36.580
told there's only one other language apart
from English spoken by the Quebec people,

00:20:36.580 --> 00:20:41.899
the French language. And yet, every five years
or so, there is a demand for cessation and

00:20:41.899 --> 00:20:44.980
there's some kind of accommodation for the
time being and we never know when Canada is

00:20:44.980 --> 00:20:51.330
going to break up. You see a tiny country
like Belgium, for instance, again two languages

00:20:51.330 --> 00:20:54.980
and every other day there's a fight breaking
out. Right now I'm told that there's no government

00:20:54.980 --> 00:20:57.621
in office there. They're figuring out who
should be the Prime Minister.

00:20:57.621 --> 00:21:04.730
You see Sri Lanka, our own southern neighbor,
there's only one other language, Sinhalese,

00:21:04.730 --> 00:21:10.139
the main language of the country. And the
minority, northern Tamil's, they spoke the

00:21:10.139 --> 00:21:15.509
Tamil language. And because the country did
not know how to reconcile the linguistic aspirations

00:21:15.509 --> 00:21:20.799
of these two groups, there was a bloody civil
war, tens of thousands of people died, one

00:21:20.799 --> 00:21:25.019
of the most murderous terrorist groups was
on rampage for decades, and only recently

00:21:25.019 --> 00:21:29.919
they have been able to overcome the terrorist
group and hopefully, they'll learn the lesson.

00:21:29.919 --> 00:21:34.250
And now the indications are that they are
trying to follow the Indian model of federalism.

00:21:34.250 --> 00:21:43.409
And India, in contrast, there are at least
18 major languages. It's not like China where

00:21:43.409 --> 00:21:48.600
Mandarin is spoken by an estimated 85% of
the people. And all the other ethnic nationalities,

00:21:48.600 --> 00:21:54.389
apart from Han Chinese, there are only 15%
of the people. In India, the largest language

00:21:54.389 --> 00:21:58.429
is spoken only by about 40% people, 40 to
45% people, Hindi.

00:21:58.429 --> 00:22:03.160
In that again, there are so many dialects
that Brij Puri is different from the chaste

00:22:03.160 --> 00:22:11.269
Hindi for let's say, Bhopal or Indore. And
other language, second biggest language, Telugu,

00:22:11.269 --> 00:22:18.240
is spoken by about 8 to 8½% of the people.
All other languages are now after order; 8%,

00:22:18.240 --> 00:22:19.900
6%, 5%, etc.

00:22:19.900 --> 00:22:26.800
And yet, despite having 18 languages, each
of them with their own literature, their own

00:22:26.800 --> 00:22:33.730
culture, their own tradition, and their own
history for centuries, some for millennia.

00:22:33.730 --> 00:22:39.990
India could actually unite all of them if
the federalism today matured. When the Constitution

00:22:39.990 --> 00:22:45.100
was written, while we were a federal country
it was actually quasi-federal.

00:22:45.100 --> 00:22:49.929
The federal government was more in command
because the founding fathers were terrified

00:22:49.929 --> 00:22:54.059
of the possibility of further vulcanization
of India, given the experience of partition

00:22:54.059 --> 00:23:00.090
in India in 1947. But, over the past 25 years,
one of the great things that happened in India

00:23:00.090 --> 00:23:04.760
is this federalism has now become very mature.
The states have come into their own. They

00:23:04.760 --> 00:23:10.039
have now considerable leeway in deciding things,
and in deciding their own des-, their own

00:23:10.039 --> 00:23:11.340
destinies.

00:23:11.340 --> 00:23:15.620
But the tragedy is the states in turn have
not recognized the need to encourage local

00:23:15.620 --> 00:23:22.040
communities to be self-governing. They spread
a constitutional injunction and we have huge

00:23:22.040 --> 00:23:30.360
amendments in 1994, running into 7,700 words.
If you compare that with American Constitution,

00:23:30.360 --> 00:23:38.159
the whole of American Constitution today some
222 years after it was written, it has some

00:23:38.159 --> 00:23:39.230
7,400 words.

00:23:39.230 --> 00:23:46.730
Our provisions relating to local governments
alone, they run into 7,700 words. And yet,

00:23:46.730 --> 00:23:52.909
we created over-structured, under-powered
local governments and the bureaucracy, of

00:23:52.909 --> 00:23:58.549
which I was a member for a long time, the
state legislatures, of which I'm a member

00:23:58.549 --> 00:24:03.500
currently, these two have conspired to ensure
that the local governments are enfeebled.

00:24:03.500 --> 00:24:10.419
There is absolutely no desire in India to
really empower the communities and to see

00:24:10.419 --> 00:24:14.920
that the people who can preside over their
own destinies. Unless India recognizes the

00:24:14.920 --> 00:24:20.679
merit of decentralization, a very complex
and lost country, we will never be able to

00:24:20.679 --> 00:24:24.590
deliver services. Without local government
empowerment, you cannot have a linkage between

00:24:24.590 --> 00:24:26.970
authority and accountability.

00:24:26.970 --> 00:24:31.559
You cannot have a clear understanding in the
minds of the people between their word and

00:24:31.559 --> 00:24:37.289
public good that results from that. And most
of all, you cannot have a link between taxes

00:24:37.289 --> 00:24:42.320
and services rendered. And therefore, there'll
be always a reluctance to pay taxes.

00:24:42.320 --> 00:24:48.240
In India, tax avoidance is a national sport.
I'm sure many of us dislike to pay taxes,

00:24:48.240 --> 00:24:53.210
but in India we really elevate that to a very
high quality sport. Our tax to GDP ratio,

00:24:53.210 --> 00:24:59.899
even today is only about 18%. That means only
18% of the GDP is collected by any government

00:24:59.899 --> 00:25:06.970
at any level; federal, local, or state towards
taxes. Compare that with the United States,

00:25:06.970 --> 00:25:12.519
it's about 40% in this country. Go to Europe.
Most countries have 50%. Some countries are

00:25:12.519 --> 00:25:18.740
60%. Now we might not go to 60% or 50%, but
to actually have a decent, functioning state

00:25:18.740 --> 00:25:23.139
of fulfilling responsibilities, the tax rates
must go higher. There must be greater tax

00:25:23.139 --> 00:25:24.190
compliance.

00:25:24.190 --> 00:25:28.060
That never happen as long as the bulk of the
people of India don't notice the link between

00:25:28.060 --> 00:25:33.549
the taxes they pay and the services they get.
And therefore, they'll be always more towards

00:25:33.549 --> 00:25:39.470
getting something in the, on co-, on the quick.
There'll be always a desire for short term

00:25:39.470 --> 00:25:43.710
maximization. Like, "Make us some freebie;
this rice, or this free power, or this free

00:25:43.710 --> 00:25:47.480
color TV. Because I know there's something
tangible that I get and I don't know what

00:25:47.480 --> 00:25:51.059
else I'll get anyway. Therefore, that's all
I expect from politics and let the country

00:25:51.059 --> 00:25:55.470
be damned." If that is to be changed, people
must see where the tax money is going and

00:25:55.470 --> 00:25:58.370
they must understand alternative uses for
the tax money.

00:25:58.370 --> 00:26:01.710
For all these reasons, we have to empower
the local governments. The way, for instance,

00:26:01.710 --> 00:26:07.330
to change despite being an autocratic regime,
has actually been trying to do. The second

00:26:07.330 --> 00:26:14.610
major change required is "rule of law". Normally,
India has an impeccable system of rule of

00:26:14.610 --> 00:26:15.610
law.

00:26:15.610 --> 00:26:19.299
The judiciary is independent, the Supreme
Court is pretty strong, perhaps not as strong

00:26:19.299 --> 00:26:24.830
as the United States, but next to U-, US,
the judiciary is the strongest in the world.

00:26:24.830 --> 00:26:30.269
We have many independent constitutional organs,
like the Election Commission, the world's

00:26:30.269 --> 00:26:35.299
most powerful Election Commission. The election
law deciding body. And many of the organs.

00:26:35.299 --> 00:26:38.040
But, nevertheless, the rule of law is pretty
weak.

00:26:38.040 --> 00:26:43.029
The norms are different from the practice.
The police are entirely under the control

00:26:43.029 --> 00:26:47.580
of the political institute in almost every
state in the country. We cannot even conceive

00:26:47.580 --> 00:26:52.179
of a situation like what happened in Illinois
state in your country when Rod Blagojevich,

00:26:52.179 --> 00:27:01.210
when he had tried to sell the, the Senator's
appointment for a price. He was promptly thrown

00:27:01.210 --> 00:27:07.340
out of office, he's probably politically buried
forever, and he may even go to jail.

00:27:07.340 --> 00:27:14.590
If you applied that standard in India, I'm
afraid it would 95% of us would be found wanting.

00:27:14.590 --> 00:27:19.269
And unless we actually create a system where
there's a fierce, independence of the Crime

00:27:19.269 --> 00:27:25.810
Investigation Authority, anticorruption agencies,
and independent prosecution. And speedy justice;

00:27:25.810 --> 00:27:30.460
our justice system is independent, but it's
very, very slow and ponderous. I don't want

00:27:30.460 --> 00:27:33.559
to go into details as to what needs, needs
to be done. There are simple, elegant answers

00:27:33.559 --> 00:27:34.559
to that.

00:27:34.559 --> 00:27:39.000
I, myself, as a member of the Administrative
Reforms Commission have specifically come

00:27:39.000 --> 00:27:43.499
out with series of proposals to bring about
significant changes within the bounds of our

00:27:43.499 --> 00:27:48.230
Constitution. So, the answers are evident.
But, we have to actually apply them so that

00:27:48.230 --> 00:27:56.809
the culture of "VIPs", Very Important Persons,
the culture of cronyism, the culture of patronage,

00:27:56.809 --> 00:28:01.309
the culture of those in power determining
all outcomes, even in justice system, and

00:28:01.309 --> 00:28:07.129
even when it comes to crime investigation,
unless we change these things we're in serious

00:28:07.129 --> 00:28:08.129
trouble.

00:28:08.129 --> 00:28:12.590
After all, the strength of a market economy
is that the market drop rates equal of everybody.

00:28:12.590 --> 00:28:17.870
It's a level playing field. And if the contracts
are not honored, if those in power decide

00:28:17.870 --> 00:28:22.679
what'll happen and who the next billionaire
is going to be, and those who actual do business

00:28:22.679 --> 00:28:27.940
in India are worried about how to enforce
the contracts, then obviously, they'll be

00:28:27.940 --> 00:28:33.590
a serious aback to businesses. The third big
change we require is to fight corruption.

00:28:33.590 --> 00:28:36.900
[pause]

00:28:36.900 --> 00:28:42.610
Corruption is obviously prevalent in many
countries. The Blagojevich case shows in-,

00:28:42.610 --> 00:28:48.260
America is no exception. But, in countries
like India, it's ubiquitous. It is universally

00:28:48.260 --> 00:28:52.710
believed that if you want to do business in
India, you have to be corrupt. Countries like

00:28:52.710 --> 00:28:56.909
the US have the Foreign Corrupt Practices
Act, which is now later adopted by the European

00:28:56.909 --> 00:29:03.690
Commission. And eventually now has become
the United Nations Convention against Corruption.

00:29:03.690 --> 00:29:07.990
Nevertheless, the fact is in many countries,
if you want to actually do serious business,

00:29:07.990 --> 00:29:14.019
unless you please those in government or in
politics, you cannot move forward. Un-, unless

00:29:14.019 --> 00:29:20.730
that is changed, I'm afraid any economic growth
will be stalled. If you want to contain corruption

00:29:20.730 --> 00:29:25.450
again, the answers are self-evident. What
you have done to Rod Blagojevich in this country

00:29:25.450 --> 00:29:31.890
must be possible for everybody in India: speedy
justice, confiscation of properties, throwing

00:29:31.890 --> 00:29:37.540
them in jail, getting them out of politics,
those who are corrupt and creating a mechanism

00:29:37.540 --> 00:29:43.110
for political campaign finance. We have an
excellent law on campaign finance in India

00:29:43.110 --> 00:29:49.010
enacted in 2003. Works at the moment and I
was privileged to be a part of that, is largely

00:29:49.010 --> 00:29:52.289
responsible for bringing about that law; it's
an excellent law.

00:29:52.289 --> 00:29:58.450
In the United States, for instance, in the
wake of Watergate in 1970s, you brought in

00:29:58.450 --> 00:30:03.639
the Campaign Finance Reform Law after Nixon's
resignation. But since then, for about 40

00:30:03.639 --> 00:30:09.940
years, there's been no serious change. And
then came, for about 30-35 years, and then

00:30:09.940 --> 00:30:14.090
came the Feingold-McCain Law, which is actually
a feeble legislation to improve the campaign

00:30:14.090 --> 00:30:18.539
finance system. India has arguably one of
the finest campaign finance laws, except that

00:30:18.539 --> 00:30:23.299
it has simply not been implemented. The parties
don't care about it. Ours is perhaps the only

00:30:23.299 --> 00:30:26.690
party in India that goes by that in letter
in spirit.

00:30:26.690 --> 00:30:32.350
Unless we make it mandatory to actually implement
that, and unless world banks exist, we are

00:30:32.350 --> 00:30:37.290
in serious trouble. But meanwhile, we have
to address the challenges of corruption by

00:30:37.290 --> 00:30:42.419
institutional mechanisms, by creating an independent,
strong, anti-corruption agency. And independent

00:30:42.419 --> 00:30:49.409
prosecution by punishing swiftly and surely
the corrupt people by setting a strong example,

00:30:49.409 --> 00:30:55.879
punitive example, and by doing several other
things that many other countries have successfully

00:30:55.879 --> 00:30:58.570
done to curb corruption substantially.

00:30:58.570 --> 00:31:06.139
Finally, politics is about incentive, just
like economics. If, in a poor country like

00:31:06.139 --> 00:31:11.521
India, word-buying is what gets you to the
winning post, I suspect people will continue

00:31:11.521 --> 00:31:15.440
to buy the words, many people will continue
to sell the words. If the buyer and seller

00:31:15.440 --> 00:31:22.531
are happy, no law, no constitution can really
set that right. We have to change the incentives.

00:31:22.531 --> 00:31:27.450
The Indian electoral system is a legacy of
the colonial Britain. It's not at all a rational

00:31:27.450 --> 00:31:31.980
system. It's utterly irrational. I believe
Attlee, who was the Prime Minister of Britain

00:31:31.980 --> 00:31:36.409
at that time, actually argued in favor of
other models like, the American presidential

00:31:36.409 --> 00:31:42.330
system and the European proportional representation
system. But the Indians said, "No, we are

00:31:42.330 --> 00:31:46.090
more British than all of you guys. We'll have
to pursue with your own electoral system even

00:31:46.090 --> 00:31:47.419
if we get rid of you."

00:31:47.419 --> 00:31:53.730
And that's actually happening today. In Britain,
except in the House of Commons, in every other

00:31:53.730 --> 00:31:59.500
election they're going up this old-fashioned
First Past-the-Post system. In the regional

00:31:59.500 --> 00:32:05.649
parliaments of Scotland, Northern Wales, and
Ireland, this is misproportionately based.

00:32:05.649 --> 00:32:11.010
In local elections, it's proportionately based.
Europe and Ireland proportionally based. London

00:32:11.010 --> 00:32:17.369
City, an electorate executive, an electorate
mayor, like now Boris Johnson is in, is the

00:32:17.369 --> 00:32:18.369
mayor.

00:32:18.369 --> 00:32:23.379
Utterly the first mayor in this new mode of
electionist Ken Livingston. India is the only

00:32:23.379 --> 00:32:28.289
country that is sticking with the old-fashioned
British best Minister, First-Past-the-Post

00:32:28.289 --> 00:32:32.249
model. It appears that Britain may actually
be changing back to the House of Commons level,

00:32:32.249 --> 00:32:37.570
also. We all know what happened in the last
week when the two parties for the first time

00:32:37.570 --> 00:32:43.080
after Second World War in Britain, headed
by Cameron and Nick Clegg, they all joined

00:32:43.080 --> 00:32:45.639
forces to form a coalition government.

00:32:45.639 --> 00:32:50.210
And eventually, in the next two, three years,
we may well see in Britain a shift to some

00:32:50.210 --> 00:32:56.230
sort of proportionate representation. The
reason why India requires a shift is if one

00:32:56.230 --> 00:33:02.960
word extra means victory, one word less means
defeat, in an abjectly poor country where

00:33:02.960 --> 00:33:07.970
the political culture is already considerably
damaged, word buying is rampant. Word buying

00:33:07.970 --> 00:33:12.039
will continue, corruption will continue, politics
will be distorted.

00:33:12.039 --> 00:33:16.120
We have to change it to a system where if
you vote this way, that way, it don't matter,

00:33:16.120 --> 00:33:21.789
it's the person that the votes to get. It's
not how much you control the constituency.

00:33:21.789 --> 00:33:28.529
As a local zemindar as we call it, a local
chief, a man with complete clout, complete

00:33:28.529 --> 00:33:33.460
domination of the local population. That's
what really gives political dividends in India

00:33:33.460 --> 00:33:38.460
today. We have to change it to a system where
it's the major party and the candidates. And

00:33:38.460 --> 00:33:42.409
the platform of the political party, rather
than the news offered to individuals to get

00:33:42.409 --> 00:33:50.190
the marginal vote that will determine the
political outcomes. If we do these things,

00:33:50.190 --> 00:33:56.669
then we could have probably change India's
political system from the 19th-century archaic

00:33:56.669 --> 00:34:01.521
model to something approximate in the 21st
century. And our economy and our politics

00:34:01.521 --> 00:34:06.299
can co-exist.
Einstein once said, "Twentieth century is

00:34:06.299 --> 00:34:11.820
characterized by perfection of means and confusion
of ends." Indian politicians have mastered

00:34:11.820 --> 00:34:17.160
the art of acquiring power. They perfected
their means. But what power is about, in terms

00:34:17.160 --> 00:34:21.650
of outcomes, is something that eludes us all
the time. There's hardly any change in respect

00:34:21.650 --> 00:34:27.230
of what happens, no matter who is in office.
And that's what should be changed in India.

00:34:27.230 --> 00:34:32.429
I believe Indian people are alive to this
challenges. They are capable of addressing

00:34:32.429 --> 00:34:36.550
them, but they require an urgent push from
all over the world with our compatriots of

00:34:36.550 --> 00:34:42.640
Indians. Indian compatriots are there. People
of Indian origin is there, are there.

00:34:42.640 --> 00:34:47.320
The businesses of India, all Indian businesses,
they must argue for change because they must

00:34:47.320 --> 00:34:52.230
not think politics is different from economics.
There is a notion in business circles that

00:34:52.230 --> 00:34:56.550
what will do business isn't related to what,
what kind of politics takes shape. Politics

00:34:56.550 --> 00:35:01.050
has a decisive influence on the way businesses
take shape and the way economic growth trajectory

00:35:01.050 --> 00:35:05.810
takes shape. And unless we address the larger
questions of politics without being partisan,

00:35:05.810 --> 00:35:11.930
without really getting into who should be
in power, but focusing on what should be the

00:35:11.930 --> 00:35:13.640
outcomes.

00:35:13.640 --> 00:35:21.760
Unless we do that, economy itself is in peril.
Indian businesses are now slowly awakening

00:35:21.760 --> 00:35:27.840
themselves to this reality. We require a change
fundamentally. I believe we will change. When

00:35:27.840 --> 00:35:35.420
status quo is unsustainable, change is inevitable.
That's why the Berlin Wall fell in 1989. It

00:35:35.420 --> 00:35:39.640
did not fall because of any bullets or warfare;
it fell because the people voted with their

00:35:39.640 --> 00:35:43.880
feet. Because they could see the contrast
between what's happening across the borders,

00:35:43.880 --> 00:35:48.880
across the wall, and in their own society.
And they could not take it any longer.

00:35:48.880 --> 00:35:53.550
And no society could depress its people forever.
And a democratic society will change when

00:35:53.550 --> 00:35:58.800
people want it adequately, but people must
be awakened to the possibilities of change.

00:35:58.800 --> 00:36:03.550
But the danger is change will still happen;
it will not be the right kind of change. Twenty

00:36:03.550 --> 00:36:10.771
years ago, there was a very popular story
in Moscow. I believe hundreds of people were

00:36:10.771 --> 00:36:16.830
queuing in front of a Russian shop for a few
crumbs of bread in Moscow City, on a bitter,

00:36:16.830 --> 00:36:24.160
biting, cold, winter morning. They waited
and waited but there was no bread in sight.

00:36:24.160 --> 00:36:27.080
When young man lost his temper after some
time, he said, "I'm sick and tired of it.

00:36:27.080 --> 00:36:32.220
I'll go and kill the General Secretary in
Kremlin." And they stormed off in protest.

00:36:32.220 --> 00:36:35.180
The others still waited patiently because
they know there was still the midnight knock,

00:36:35.180 --> 00:36:41.480
there was still the Secret Police, the Gestapo,
or whatever they called it in, in Soviet Union.

00:36:41.480 --> 00:36:46.770
There's still the concentration camps, the
GULAGs, therefore they all waited very quietly

00:36:46.770 --> 00:36:52.340
and patiently. The same man came back after
two hours. The others still were waiting and

00:36:52.340 --> 00:36:55.131
there was no bread in sight. They're all gathered
around him and asked him, "What happened?

00:36:55.131 --> 00:36:58.670
Have you killed the General Secretary?" He
said, "A riot in Kremlin can rob the store

00:36:58.670 --> 00:37:03.470
now, children are hungry at home, please tell
us what happened?" This young man said, "You

00:37:03.470 --> 00:37:07.610
know, I went there to kill the General Secretary,
but there was a much longer queue waiting

00:37:07.610 --> 00:37:08.610
there."

00:37:08.610 --> 00:37:11.170
[laughter]

00:37:11.170 --> 00:37:18.970
This story was recounted in every single household
of Soviet Union in all the 15 republics at

00:37:18.970 --> 00:37:23.700
the time. People laughed about it, but they
did nothing about it.

00:37:23.700 --> 00:37:30.080
Change did come in 1991, but not the kind
of change any Soviet citizen wanted. Change

00:37:30.080 --> 00:37:34.090
will always come. It will always overtake
us, eventually, every society. The challenge

00:37:34.090 --> 00:37:39.560
is, is it the kind of change we all need,
we all desire and that will be positive? Or

00:37:39.560 --> 00:37:45.630
is it the change we'll have to submit ourselves
to and pay the price for? That's the challenge

00:37:45.630 --> 00:37:53.280
facing Indian people, and Indian politicians,
Indian civil servants, and Indian businessmen.

00:37:53.280 --> 00:37:58.420
I believe we are all capable of rising to
the challenge and fulfilling our potential

00:37:58.420 --> 00:38:01.790
and becoming one of the great economies on
one of the most moderating influences in the

00:38:01.790 --> 00:38:08.300
modern world, in a complex, ever-changing,
unpredictable world. But only if we set our

00:38:08.300 --> 00:38:13.890
house in order today. And I believe the stakes
for the world are as great as they are for

00:38:13.890 --> 00:38:18.440
India, because what happens to one system
of humanity cannot but impact the rest of

00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:24.590
the world. And I believe the rest of the world
is actually waiting for this, this caged lion,

00:38:24.590 --> 00:38:34.050
to really find its own feet and find its own
direction. And I believe ultimately, 21st-century

00:38:34.050 --> 00:38:39.890
economy and 21st-century politics will coincide
and show the way to many other countries in

00:38:39.890 --> 00:38:44.970
emerging economies which continue to believe
that economic growth and political freedom

00:38:44.970 --> 00:38:51.970
cannot coexist. We have to prove that these
two can and must coexist. The challenge in

00:38:51.970 --> 00:38:58.840
that sense is fundamental and it's human.
Thank you.

00:38:58.840 --> 00:39:01.840
